<dl id="n38223d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38223d">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38223d"> 223(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> barmecides</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">known of barmicidal days; <cite>FW</cite> 387.21: barmaighsigheds. Joyce was familiar with the story of the Barmecides from the writings of J. C. Mangan. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 136-7:[Of Aaron the Orthodox] But a single great crime, a tragedy whose details are almost incredibly horrible, marks his reign with the stain of infamy, with a blot of blood never to be washed away. This tale, &ldquo;full of the waters of the eye,&rdquo; as Firdausi sings, is the massacre of the <mark>Barmecides</mark>. <mm class="note">Note: <cite>FW</cite> 79.6</small></blockquote> </mm> </dd></dl>
